# CompTIA A+ Core 2 - Security Measures and Their Purposes

# 2.1 Security Measures

---

# Physical Security

| Topic | One-line Explanation | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Bollards | Barriers used to stop vehicles from entering restricted areas. | Concrete posts outside a bank entrance. |
| Access control vestibule | Small secured entry area that controls one person entering at a time. | Mantrap door at a data center. |
| Badge reader | Device that scans ID badges for access authorization. | Employee taps ID card to enter office. |
| Video surveillance | Cameras used to monitor and record activities. | CCTV cameras in a parking lot. |
| Alarm systems | Systems that alert security during unauthorized access. | Burglar alarm triggered after hours. |
| Motion sensors | Devices that detect movement in restricted areas. | Motion detector activating hallway lights and alarms. |
| Door locks | Physical locks used to secure rooms and buildings. | Deadbolt lock on a server room door. |
| Equipment locks | Locks that physically secure devices from theft. | Kensington lock on a laptop. |
| Security guards | Personnel responsible for monitoring and protecting property. | Guard checking visitor IDs at entrance. |
| Fences | Physical barriers used to restrict unauthorized access. | Metal fence surrounding a company compound. |

---

# Physical Access Security

| Topic | One-line Explanation | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Key fobs | Small electronic devices used for secure entry authentication. | Employee taps RFID fob to unlock door. |
| Smart cards | Cards with embedded chips used for authentication. | CAC card used in government offices. |
| Mobile digital key | Smartphone-based credential used for secure access. | Phone app unlocking hotel room door. |
| Keys | Physical metal objects used to unlock doors or equipment. | Traditional office key. |

---

# Biometrics

| Topic | One-line Explanation | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Retina scanner | Uses retina blood vessel patterns for identification. | Retina scan at military facility. |
| Fingerprint scanner | Uses fingerprint patterns for authentication. | Phone fingerprint unlock. |
| Palm print scanner | Uses palm characteristics for identity verification. | Palm scanner at secure lab entrance. |
| Facial recognition technology (FRT) | Identifies users based on facial features. | Face unlock on smartphones. |
| Voice recognition technology | Uses voice patterns to verify identity. | Voice login for banking support. |

---

# Additional Physical Security

| Topic | One-line Explanation | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Lighting | Improves visibility and discourages unauthorized activity. | Floodlights around parking area. |
| Magnetometers | Devices that detect metal objects for security screening. | Metal detector at airport entrance. |

---

# Logical Security

| Topic | One-line Explanation | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Principle of least privilege | Users receive only minimum permissions required for their job. | Employee can view files but cannot delete them. |
| Zero Trust model | Security model that assumes no user/device is trusted automatically. | MFA required even inside company network. |
| Access control lists (ACLs) | Rules that define permitted or denied access to resources. | Firewall ACL blocking unauthorized IPs. |
| Multifactor authentication (MFA) | Uses multiple authentication methods for stronger security. | Password plus fingerprint login. |

---

# MFA Methods

| Topic | One-line Explanation | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Email | Authentication code sent through email. | Login verification code via Gmail. |
| Hardware token | Physical device generating authentication codes. | RSA security token. |
| Authenticator application | Mobile app generating login verification codes. | Google Authenticator app. |
| Short Message Service (SMS) | One-time code sent through text message. | Bank sends OTP by SMS. |
| Voice call | Authentication code delivered by phone call. | Automated security verification call. |
| Time-based one-time password (TOTP) | Temporary code generated based on time synchronization. | 30-second rotating code in Authenticator app. |
| One-time password/passcode (OTP) | Single-use authentication code. | One-time banking verification code. |

---

# Identity and Access Technologies

| Topic | One-line Explanation | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) | Enables secure authentication sharing between services. | Logging into Salesforce using company Microsoft account. |
| Single sign-on (SSO) | Allows one login for multiple applications. | One login for Gmail, Drive, and Calendar. |
| Just-in-time access | Grants temporary privileged access only when needed. | Admin receives elevated rights for 1 hour. |
| Privileged access management (PAM) | Controls and monitors administrator-level accounts. | Admin credentials stored in secure vault. |
| Mobile device management (MDM) | Centrally manages and secures mobile devices. | IT remotely wiping lost company phone. |
| Data loss prevention (DLP) | Prevents unauthorized sharing of sensitive data. | Blocking employees from emailing confidential files. |
| Identity access management (IAM) | Manages user identities and access permissions. | Creating employee accounts with role-based permissions. |
| Directory services | Centralized system for managing users and resources. | Microsoft Active Directory. |
